Headline: Virgin Media To Make Complaint To OFT On BSkyB - Report
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Richard Branson's Virgin Media Inc. (VMED) is to make a fresh complaint to the Office of Fair Trading after last week's row with rival British Sky Broadcasting Group PLC (BSY), The Independent on Sunday reports.   The group is to tell the OFT and regulator Ofcom that BSkyB's refusal to drop the price for some its channels is further evidence of the dominance of the market, the paper said.    Virgin Media was relaunched in February after a deal that saw U.K. entrepreneur Richard Branson take a stake in the company and sell his Virgin Mobile unit to NTL, which took on the Virgin Media brand.    The Sunday Telegraph reported separately that just 100 customers a day have canceled subscriptions since Sky One was withdrawan from the cable service last week.   Virgin Media couldn't immediately be reached for comment.   Newspaper Web sites: http://www.independent.co.uk                        http://www.telegraph.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9295     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 06:19 ET (11:19 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Star Cruises To Withdraw From Singapore Casino-Resort
Story: SINGAPORE (Dow Jones)--Genting International Ltd. (G13.SG) said Sunday that Star Cruises Ltd. (S21.SG), its partner in the development of a S$5.2 billion ($US) casino-resort in Singapore, has agreed to withdraw from the project.   Star Cruises will be offering its 25% stake in Resorts World at Sentosa to Genting International for a price that will be agreed at a later date, Genting International said in a statement.   Taking 100% control of the Sentosa casino-resort project will help Genting International get a casino license from the Singapore government, the company said.   The withdrawal of Star Cruises comes after the Singapore government Tuesday said Genting International, Star and their associates have to prove they can run a clean gambling venue if they want a casino operating license.   That warning was triggered by Genting International and Star Cruises, both units of Malaysian gambling group Genting Bhd. (3182.KU), announcing a Macau casino-and-hotel deal with Stanley Ho, a controversial businessman who is alleged to have links to organized crime in the former Portuguese enclave.   On Saturday, Genting International said it had agreed to sell its 25% stake in the joint venture company that is making the Macau investment to Star Cruises for HK$58.5 million.     -By Stephen Wright, Dow Jones Newswires; 65 6415 4151; stephen.wright@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 04:51 ET (09:51 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: HP Interested To Acquiring Stake In SAP AG -Report
Story: BERLIN (Dow Jones)--Hewlett-Packard Co. (HPQ) is interested in acquiring an equity stake in German software firm SAP AG (SAP), German magazine WirtschaftsWoche reports in an advance copy of Monday's edition.   The magazine said that it has picked up on this information in the U.S., without elaborating.   WirtschaftsWoche also reported, citing Frankfurt-based banking sources, that private equity bankers of Silver Lake will travel to Germany mid-March, to negotiate the acquisition of an equity stake in SAP, possibly from one of the three founders which still each hold around 10% in SAP.   Silver Lake aims to set up a new fund of EUR7.5 billion for its planned investment in SAP, the magazine added.   SAP declined to comment, but reiterated its earlier statement that its founders remain committed to the company.   Magazine Web site: http://www.wiwo.de     -Berlin Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-30-2888-410.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 08:56 ET (13:56 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Sainsbury Suitors To Decide Shortly On Possible Bid-Reports
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--The private equity consortium circling J Sainsbury PLC (SBRY.LN) will decide within eight days whether to abandon a possible GBP11 billion bid or to launch a formal offer, The Independent on Sunday newspaper reported.   Citing unnamed sources close to the deal, the paper said the private equity groups' decision to bring matters to a head has been triggered by a wave of negative publicity the bid has created.   On Feb. 2, CVC Capital Partners Ltd., Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. Ltd. and Blackstone Group International Ltd. said they were at the "preliminary stages of assessing" a bid for Sainsbury. No price was mentioned in their brief statement to the London Stock Exchange.   Citing unnamed advisers, The Observer newspaper reported that the deal is on a knife edge and the private equity group is prepared to walk away from a bid following a strong rise in Sainsbury's share price.   The Mail on Sunday paper said separately that Sainsbury's may ask the Takeover Panel to issue a so-called "put up or shut up" notice to the private equity suitors.   Officials at Sainsbury's or the private equity companies couldn't immediately be reached for comment.   Newspaper Web sites: http://www.independent.co.uk                        http://www.dailymail.co.uk                        http://www.observer.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9295     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 05:40 ET (10:40 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: 'Wild Hogs' Makes No 1 Box Office Debut
Story: LOS ANGELES (AP)--The biker buddy comedy "Wild Hogs" and its ensemble cast of John Travolta, Martin Lawrence, William H. Macy and Tim Allen was the weekend box office champ with a $38 million take, according to studio estimates Sunday.   It was Walt Disney Co.'s (DIS) biggest March opening ever. It was also the largest-ever debut for the 53-year-old Travolta as well as the best non-animated movie debut for Allen, who is also 53. Macy turns 57 next week and Lawrence turns 42 next month.   "It's so easy to see in the material how much fun they were having together. The audience was looking for that first great comedy of the year," Disney president of distribution Chuck Viane said.   "Wild Hogs" performed well beyond expectations, said Paul Dergarabedian, president of box-office tracker Media By Numbers. It was expected to be No. 1 with earnings in the $25 million range, he said.   "It's just astonishing," Dergarabedian said. "It was the perfect vehicle for these four stars. A combination of star power, great concept and great marketing was responsible.   "This is not an Oscar contender, but it's a fun time at the movies. You know, sometimes its just about escapism."   No other films were even close to "Wild Hogs."   The No. 2 movie was the thriller "Zodiac," which debuted with $13.1 million. "Ghost Rider" fell to No. 3 in its third week of release with $11.5 million, "Bridge to Terabithia" was fourth with $8.6 million and "The Number 23" dropped to fifth with $7.1 million in its second week.   Eddie Murphy's "Norbit" continued to draw crowds, placing sixth in its fourth week of release with a $6.4 million  take and boosting its cumulative tally to $83 million.   "Music & Lyrics" was No. 7 with $4.9 million  and the new movie "Black Snake Moan," about an aging black man who chains a young white woman to a radiator to cure her of her demons, only took in $4 million for eighth place.   Rounding out the Top 10 was ninth place "Reno 911!: Miami" with $3.8 million  and "Breach" with $3.5 million.   Estimated ticket sales for Friday through Sunday at U.S. and Canadian theaters, according to Media By Numbers LLC. Final figures will be released Monday.   1. "Wild Hogs," $38 million.   2. "Zodiac," $13.1 million.   3. "Ghost Rider," $11.5 million.   4. "Bridge to Terabithia," $8.6 million.   5. "The Number 23," $7.1 million.   6. "Norbit," $6.4 million.   7. "Music & Lyrics," $4.9 million.   8. "Black Snake Moan," $4 million.   9. "Reno 911!: Miami" $3.8 million.   10. "Breach," $3.5 million.   ---   Universal Pictures and Focus Features are owned by NBC Universal, a joint venture of General Electric Co. (GE) and Vivendi (12777.FR) Universal; Sony Pictures, Sony Screen Gems and Sony Pictures Classics are units of Sony Corp. (SNE); DreamWorks, Paramount and Paramount Vantage are divisions of Viacom Inc. (VIA); Disney's parent is The Walt Disney Co.; Miramax is a division of The Walt Disney Co.; 20th Century Fox, Fox Searchlight Pictures and Fox Atomic are owned by News Corp. (NWS); Warner Bros., New Line, Warner Independent and Picturehouse are units of Time Warner Inc. (TMX); MGM is owned by a consortium of Providence Equity Partners, Texas Pacific Group, Sony Corp., Comcast Corp. (CMCSA), DLJ Merchant Banking Partners and Quadrangle Group; Lionsgate is owned by Lionsgate Entertainment Corp. (LGF); IFC Films is owned by Rainbow Media Holdings, a subsidiary of Cablevision Systems Corp. (CVC).     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 14:29 ET (19:29 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Dubai Govt Firm Buys NYC's Mandarin Oriental Hotel
Story: DUBAI (AP)--Dubai's government bolstered its holdings of New York City real estate, announcing Sunday that its Istithmar PJSC holding company had purchased a majority stake in Manhattan's five-star Mandarin Oriental hotel.   The $340 million purchase of the Mandarin Oriental, part of the Time Warner Center on Manhattan's Columbus Circle, adds to the growing U.S. real estate portfolio held by the Arab world's financial powerhouse.   Istithmar's New York properties include the W Hotel on Union Square, the Knickerbocker Hotel on Times Square and commercial buildings at 280 Park Avenue, 230 Park Avenue and 450 Lexington Avenue. The firm also owns the Hotel Washington in Washington D.C.   "We're building a portfolio of both luxury and budget hotels in key target markets around the world," said Joe Sita, chief executive of Istithmar's hotels group.   Another Dubai government-held firm, Jumeirah International, owns the Jumeirah Essex House hotel on Manhattan's Central Park South.   Istithmar said in a prepared release that it bought a 73% share of the Mandarin Oriental, buying 25% from Mandarin Oriental Hotel Group and 48% from a joint venture between New York-based developers Apollo Real Estate Advisors LP and Related Cos.   Istithmar already holds 2.4% of Time Warner shares and options.   Dubai, one of seven city-states that form the U.S.-allied United Arab Emirates, has grown into a global financial capital despite its lack of petroleum reserves. The city has instead lured energy revenues from neighboring states through liberal investment and residency laws, booming financial and real estate sectors, and the Mideast's largest port and airport.   Istithmar is a sister company to the Dubai government-owned Dubai Ports World, one of the world's largest ports operators. DP World's purchase last year of operations in six U.S. ports touched off a political firestorm in the U.S. Congress, which cited security reasons for voting to force the Dubai company to sell its U.S. holdings.   The imbroglio damaged relations between Washington and the Emirates, where many said U.S. opposition to the deal smacked of anti-Arab bias.   American International Group Inc. (AIG), an insurance conglomerate, received approval last month from U.S. federal antitrust authorities to complete its purchase of the ports.   Last July, Istithmar paid $300 million for New York-based specialty retailer Loehmann's. Istithmar said it planned to increase the number of Loehmann's stores to 100 from 60 over the next five years and open a flagship on Manhattan's Upper West Side.   Elsewhere, Istithmar bought a $1 billion stake in London-based bank Standard Chartered Plc and acquired London's Adelphi building for $567 million .   Istithmar Hotels, founded less than a year ago, has already amassed a $3 billion portfolio of hotels and resorts. Besides those mentioned, it holds a portion of Kerzner Group, the developer and operator of Atlantis Resorts and luxury resort One and Only; as well as the franchise for budget hotel chain easyHotels in the Middle East, North Africa and South Asia.   Jumeirah's other properties include a pair of luxury hotels in London, the Jumeirah Carlton Tower and the Jumeirah Lowndes Hotel. Jumeirah is building a luxury resort in Bermuda as well as hotels and resorts in China, Thailand and the Middle East.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 04:48 ET (09:48 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: ASIAN STOCK FOCUS: Steel Shares May Rise Under New Rules
Story: By James Simms     Of DOW JONES NEWSWIRES     Tokyo -- Poison pills, share buybacks, friendly alliances and cross-shareholdings -- Japanese steelmakers have tried them all to become less appealing takeover targets to foreign steel companies. New antitrust rules could make it even harder for a would-be foreign acquirer to get its hands on a Japanese steel producer.   This could support shares of Nippon Steel (5401.TO), the nation's largest producer by output and revenue, and JFE Holdings (5411.TO), the No. 2 maker. Their shares have risen in recent months on speculation that they could become acquisition targets.   The new guidelines, set to take effect in April, lower the hurdle for mergers among Japanese companies because they allow Japan's antitrust watchdog to consider the market share the combined company would have in the world, not just within Japan.   The regulations, which hew to global standards, would make it easier for a major Japanese steelmaker to buy a local rival and possibly become big enough to prevent being taken over by an overseas competitor. It also would allow a Japanese steel company to make a friendly "white knight" bid -- where a company tries to rescue a firm from an unwanted advance -- were another domestic steel producer to face a takeover threat from a foreign firm.   Japanese steel companies would prefer a domestic partner because of concerns about steelmaking technology falling into foreign hands. There is also an issue of national pride for them as one of the drivers of the nation's early 20th-century industrialization and post-World War II high-speed expansion, and as suppliers of components for Japan's current industrial might.   The rules might spark more consolidation among Japanese companies, says Nobuo Sayama, a partner at M&A boutique GCA in Tokyo. "Whether the motive is as a white knight or a pre-emptive, defensive merger, consolidation will speed up," he says.   The regulatory changes come at a time when an increasing number of foreign companies are interested in buying Japanese companies, analysts and bankers say. After Mittal Steel, of the Netherlands, last year made its hostile bid for Luxembourg-based Arcelor, Japanese companies feared that eventually, they, too, could be gobbled up by an acquisitive global steelmaker. (The bid for Arcelor eventually succeeded, and the two soon will be legally merged, forming the world's biggest steelmaker in terms of volume and sales.)   Arcelor Mittal hasn't indicated that it is interested in buying a Japanese steel maker.   "We are in support of further industry consolidation and as the market leader, we intend to continue to participate in such consolidation," says Luc Scheer, a spokesman for the steelmaker. "We would not comment on specific countries or opportunities, but our long-term growth focus is particularly oriented toward the potential of developing economies."   Japanese steel companies could be attractive targets. Nippon Steel, JFE and others provide major components for Japan's world-class exports such as ships, machine tools and automobiles, supplying the likes of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries and Toyota Motor. The century-old domestic industry is at the forefront of global steel-production technology. Nippon Steel has some 7,000 steelmaking patents. That compares with 5,500 at Arcelor Mittal, which has more than double the revenue and more than three times the output of the Japanese maker.   Noboru Yamamoto, a managing director at Nikko Citigroup's investment-banking unit, says Japanese steelmakers will become a "must have" for companies like Arcelor Mittal because of their technology and strong relationships with heavyweight Japanese customers.   That possibility hasn't been lost on the Japanese producers. Nippon Steel adopted a poison pill in March last year, a takeover defense that enables it to dilute an acquirer's share stake. Smaller rivals Sumitomo Metal Industries and Kobe Steel followed suit over the next month. Nippon Steel and JFE also have bought back shares to reduce the number traded on the open market and bolster their firms' valuations. JFE said Thursday that it is planning defenses against takeovers.   A Japanese trade-and-industry official said the ministry has been pressing steelmakers for "quite a while" to put in antitakeover measures, including poison pills.   The firms have been forging closer ties with friendly partners. In addition to holding shares in each other, Nippon Steel, Sumitomo and Kobe agreed in March 2006 to consult each other on what steps they might take if one of the companies comes under attack. Nippon Steel has tightened its relationship with Posco, the world's No. 3 steel producer in terms of output, and has ties with German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp.   Speculation of a hostile move on one of Japan's major integrated steelmakers has helped lift their stock prices. Even without foreign moves on them, there is the possibility of a domestic merger that would buoy their stock prices.   Nippon Steel and JFE have nearly doubled since Mittal announced its Arcelor bid Jan. 27 last year. Friday, shares of Nippon Steel rose 32 yen (27 cents), or 3.9%, to 849 yen -- compared with 429 yen when Mittal unveiled its Arcelor plan. JFE's shares, which were at 4,030 yen when Mittal first moved, rose 120 yen, or 1.7%, Friday to close at 7,350 yen.   Under the new rules, which use the same Herfindahl Hirschman Index -- a gauge of a market's concentration rather than the share of individual companies when assessing pending deals -- that U.S. and European Union regulators use, a Nippon Steel-JFE combination will be theoretically possible. Most analysts believe that under the old rules, Japanese antitrust regulators would have vetoed the idea, as a combined entity would have more than 50% of the home market. The broader scope of the new rules might allow such a merger, as the two steelmakers together have 6% of the global market.     -By James Simms, Dow Jones Newswires; 813-5255-2929; james.simms@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 17:27 ET (22:27 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: E.ON Advised To Buy Enel Stk As Move In Endesa Battle -Report
Story: BERLIN (Dow Jones)--German utility E.ON AG (EON) has been advised by bankers to acquire a stake in Italian rival Enel SpA (EN) to use as bargaining tool in its takeover bid for Spain's Endesa SA (ELE), German magazine Spiegel reports without citing its sources.   According to the magazine, the move to buy a stake of up to 25% in Enel on the international markets, has been advised by U.S. investment bank Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (GS), possibly to offer as a swap for Enel's growing Endesa stake.   E.ON wasn't immediately available for comment Sunday.   In a surprise move, Enel snapped up a big minority stake in Spain's Endesa last week, threatening to unravel E.On's EUR41 billion tender offer for Spain's largest utility just when success seemed assured.   Magazine Web site: http://www.spiegel.de     -Berlin Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 49-30-2888-410.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 06:22 ET (11:22 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: 5 Kidnapped Ethiopians Found, Eritrea Denies Involved-Report
Story: MEKELE, Ethiopia (AP)--Several Ethiopians who were kidnapped along with five Britons touring the African country's remote northeast have been found, state media reported, as archrival Eritrea on Sunday denied accusations that it was behind the kidnapping.   The state-run Ethiopian News Agency late Saturday said that five of the 13 Ethiopians in the tour group were found near the border with Eritrea, but it wasn't clear whether they had escaped or were released.   Eritrean Information Minister Ali Abdu on Sunday denied claims by senior Ethiopian officials that Eritrean commandoes seized the group Thursday. Abdu said the claims were baseless.   Relations between Ethiopia and Eritrea have been consistently strained since Eritrea gained independence from the Addis Ababa government in 1993 following a 30-year guerrilla war.   The tour group went missing Thursday while traveling in Ethiopia's Afar region, a barren expanse of ancient salt mines and volcanoes some 800 kilometers northeast of the capital, Addis Ababa. Communications to Afar are extremely difficult, but the otherworldly, moonlike landscape draws adventure travelers.   The British Broadcasting Corp., quoting unidentified government sources, said there was a "national security dimension" to the disappearance of the Britons, all of whom are employees of the British Embassy in Addis Ababa or their relatives. The British Foreign Office and the British Defense Ministry wouldn't comment on the BBC report.   Esmal Ali Sero, head of the Afar administrative region, said about 25 Eritrean "commandoes" kidnapped the British citizens along with their Ethiopian drivers and translators Thursday night. He cited local investigators.   A senior Ethiopian official in the ruling party, who asked not to be named, also said Eritreans were behind the kidnapping. He said a herder saw the British group at the Ara-ta military camp in Eritrea and reported it to the Ethiopians. Herders in Afar frequently travel between the two countries.   Tour operators in the area also said they were told by police that Eritreans in military uniforms kidnapped the Britons and burned down the house where they were staying, along with several vehicles.   A spokeswoman for the British Embassy in Addis Ababa, speaking on customary condition of anonymity, said she had no information: "We do not know where they are or who is holding them. We are not prepared to speculate."   Also Sunday, a group of French tourists who had also been missing since Thursday arrived in Mekele, the Afar region's capital, and said they hadn't been kidnapped, as was previously believed.   "Not at any time were we unsafe," said one of the tourists, who refused to give his name. He said the group simply didn't have a satellite phone and so couldn't check in with Origins Ethiopia tour group. Samson Teshome, head of Origins Ethiopia, also said the group hadn't been kidnapped.   Sources including French diplomats and local businessmen had been reporting that the French were kidnapped.   French Foreign Minister Philippe Douste-Blazy released a statement Sunday saying the group had been able to meet with an embassy representative.   "We are continuing to verify that no French person is currently in that zone," he said in the statement.   Bandits and a small rebel group operate in Afar, where the famous Ethiopian fossil of Lucy, the earliest known hominid, was discovered in 1974. The Ethiopian government requires tourists to travel in Afar with armed guards; the British and French groups were believed to have complied.   Britain sent a crisis team to Ethiopia on Saturday in an effort to obtain the release of the five Britons.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 09:27 ET (14:27 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: RHB Said To Attract Kuwait Fin House, EPF Offers- Report
Story: KUALA LUMPUR (Dow Jones)--Kuwait Finance House Malaysia Bhd. has applied to the Bank Negara Malaysia for permission to make a general offer for Rashid Hussain Bhd. (1309.KU), unit RHB Capital Bhd. (5266.KU) and unlisted RHB Bank, the Edge Weekly reported, citing unnamed sources.   The weekly newspaper said Kuwait Finance submitted the application Friday, the sources added.   On the same day, it said, the Employees Provident Fund, or EPF, received its investment panel's consent to launch a general offer for the Rashid Hussain shares it doesn't currently own.   EPF is said to be willing to pay up to 10 billion Malaysian ringgit ($2.9 billion) for those shares, the report said.   The sources added that if Bank Negara gives Kuwait Finance the green light, it will offer MYR2 per RHB share and MYR2.04 for each loan stock, and MYR7 for each RHB Capital share, the report said.     Newspaper Web site: http://www.theedgedaily.com     -By Kuala Lumpur bureau; Dow Jones Newswires; 603-2692-5254; djnews.kldowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 01:50 ET (06:50 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: China Construction Bk Chmn:No Current Plans For Mainland IPO
Story: BEIJING (Dow Jones)--China Construction Bank Corp. (0939.HK), one of the big four state-owned commercial banks in China, doesn't currently have specific plans to list in the mainland or make any overseas acquisitions, the chairman of the bank said Sunday.   Guo Shuqing, the chairman, made the remarks on the sidelines of the annual meeting of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference, an advisory body to the Chinese government. The advisory body meets annually alongside the National People's Congress, China's legislature.   China Construction Bank raised US$9.2 billion from listing in Hong Kong in October 2005. And last year the Chinese bank acquired the Hong Kong and Macau retail operations of Bank of America Corp. (BAC). Bank of America has a 8.52% stake in China Construction Bank.   -By Rick Carew, Dow Jones Newswires; (86-10) 6588-5848; rick.carew@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 05:37 ET (10:37 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Converium Board Ready To Evaluate Improved Scor Offer-Report
Story: ZURICH (Dow Jones)--Converium Holding AG's (CHR) board would evaluate a higher offer from Scor SA (SCO), if its French rival were to improve its bid for the Swiss company's shares, Markus Dennler, Chairman of the board at Converium, said in a newspaper interview Saturday.   In an interview with Swiss business newspaper Finanz und Wirtschaft, Dennler reiterated that the board considers Scor's current offer as too low and that Converium would do better on a stand-alone basis than if it was taken over by its French peer.   Scor made an unsolicited offer for Converium last month, which the Swiss company rejected. Scor, which has acquired just under a third of Converium's shares, plans to launch a public offer for Converium shares in April.   Scor's bid values Converium at around 3.1 billion Swiss franc ($2.51 billion).   Newspaper Web site: http://www.finanzinfo.ch     -Zurich Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 41-43-4438044; zurichdjnews@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 11:28 ET (16:28 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: WSJA(3/5)Heard In Japan:Steel Shares May Rise Under New Rules
Story: (From THE WALL STREET JOURNAL ASIA)     By James Simms   Tokyo -- POISON PILLS, SHARE buybacks, friendly alliances and cross-shareholdings -- Japanese steelmakers have tried them all to become less appealing takeover targets to foreign steel companies. New antitrust rules could make it even harder for a would-be foreign acquirer to get its hands on a Japanese steel producer.   This could support shares of Nippon Steel, the nation's largest producer by output and revenue, and JFE Holdings, the No. 2 maker. Their shares have risen in recent months on speculation that they could become acquisition targets.   The new guidelines, set to take effect in April, lower the hurdle for mergers among Japanese companies because they allow Japan's antitrust watchdog to consider the market share the combined company would have in the world, not just within Japan.   The regulations, which hew to global standards, would make it easier for a major Japanese steelmaker to buy a local rival and possibly become big enough to prevent being taken over by an overseas competitor. It also would allow a Japanese steel company to make a friendly "white knight" bid -- where a company tries to rescue a firm from an unwanted advance -- were another domestic steel producer to face a takeover threat from a foreign firm.   Japanese steel companies would prefer a domestic partner because of concerns about steelmaking technology falling into foreign hands. There is also an issue of national pride for them as one of the drivers of the nation's early 20th-century industrialization and post-World War II high-speed expansion, and as suppliers of components for Japan's current industrial might.   The rules might spark more consolidation among Japanese companies, says Nobuo Sayama, a partner at M&A boutique GCA in Tokyo. "Whether the motive is as a white knight or a pre-emptive, defensive merger, consolidation will speed up," he says.   The regulatory changes come at a time when an increasing number of foreign companies are interested in buying Japanese companies, analysts and bankers say. After Mittal Steel, of the Netherlands, last year made its hostile bid for Luxembourg-based Arcelor, Japanese companies feared that eventually, they, too, could be gobbled up by an acquisitive global steelmaker. (The bid for Arcelor eventually succeeded, and the two soon will be legally merged, forming the world's biggest steelmaker in terms of volume and sales.)   Arcelor Mittal hasn't indicated that it is interested in buying a Japanese steel maker.   "We are in support of further industry consolidation and as the market leader, we intend to continue to participate in such consolidation," says Luc Scheer, a spokesman for the steelmaker. "We would not comment on specific countries or opportunities, but our long-term growth focus is particularly oriented toward the potential of developing economies."   Japanese steel companies could be attractive targets. Nippon Steel, JFE and others provide major components for Japan's world-class exports such as ships, machine tools and automobiles, supplying the likes of Mitsubishi Heavy Industries and Toyota Motor. The century-old domestic industry is at the forefront of global steel-production technology. Nippon Steel has some 7,000 steelmaking patents. That compares with 5,500 at Arcelor Mittal, which has more than double the revenue and more than three times the output of the Japanese maker.   Noboru Yamamoto, a managing director at Nikko Citigroup's investment-banking unit, says Japanese steelmakers will become a "must have" for companies like Arcelor Mittal because of their technology and strong relationships with heavyweight Japanese customers.   That possibility hasn't been lost on the Japanese producers. Nippon Steel adopted a poison pill in March last year, a takeover defense that enables it to dilute an acquirer's share stake. Smaller rivals Sumitomo Metal Industries and Kobe Steel followed suit over the next month. Nippon Steel and JFE also have bought back shares to reduce the number traded on the open market and bolster their firms' valuations. JFE said Thursday that it is planning defenses against takeovers.   A Japanese trade-and-industry official said the ministry has been pressing steelmakers for "quite a while" to put in antitakeover measures, including poison pills.   The firms have been forging closer ties with friendly partners. In addition to holding shares in each other, Nippon Steel, Sumitomo and Kobe agreed in March 2006 to consult each other on what steps they might take if one of the companies comes under attack. Nippon Steel has tightened its relationship with Posco, the world's No. 3 steel producer in terms of output, and has ties with German steelmaker ThyssenKrupp.   Speculation of a hostile move on one of Japan's major integrated steelmakers has helped lift their stock prices. Even without foreign moves on them, there is the possibility of a domestic merger that would buoy their stock prices.   Nippon Steel and JFE have nearly doubled since Mittal announced its Arcelor bid Jan. 27 last year. Friday, shares of Nippon Steel rose 32 yen (27 cents), or 3.9%, to 849 yen -- compared with 429 yen when Mittal unveiled its Arcelor plan. JFE's shares, which were at 4,030 yen when Mittal first moved, rose 120 yen, or 1.7%, Friday to close at 7,350 yen.   Under the new rules, which use the same Herfindahl Hirschman Index -- a gauge of a market's concentration rather than the share of individual companies when assessing pending deals -- that U.S. and European Union regulators use, a Nippon Steel-JFE combination will be theoretically possible. Most analysts believe that under the old rules, Japanese antitrust regulators would have vetoed the idea, as a combined entity would have more than 50% of the home market. The broader scope of the new rules might allow such a merger, as the two steelmakers together have 6% of the global market.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 16:30 ET (21:30 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : Small High Growth Businesses to Receive Unprecedented Boost as NewMedia SPARK Backs Notonthehighstreet.com
Story: LONDON--(BUSINESS WIRE)--March 04, 2007--   Notonthehighstreet.com (www.notonthehighstreet.com), the UK based shopping website that supports over 500 of Britain's most creative small businesses, today announces a major development as NewMedia SPARK plc (LSE:NMS), the quoted venture capital organisation focused on early stage investments in the technology, media and telecoms sectors, becomes a significant minority shareholder in the company. In addition, Tom Teichman, Chairman and Founder of NewMedia SPARK plc, who handed over the first investment cheque to lastminute.com, joins the board of notonthehighstreet.com with immediate effect.     Notonthehighstreet.com launched in April 2006 selling high quality original products from 130 of Britain's best small businesses. Such has been its rapid success that, in less than a year, it now helps over 500 carefully selected quality small businesses to sell over 10,000 products under its unique umbrella shopping website giving an original product offering and service to consumers that is not available on the high street.     NewMedia SPARK's investment will enable even more small businesses to become part of the notonthehighstreet.com community and to build notonthehighstreet.com into a brand that is synonymous with small, creative lifestyle businesses and products.     Founders of notonthehighstreet.com, Holly Tucker and Sophie Cornish, commented: "NewMedia SPARK's investment in the company is the most exciting news for us, and will make a huge commercial and competitive difference to the small businesses we already support and to the new ones that we look forward to joining us. This investment will enable us to accelerate our expansion plans and launch internationally over the next two years, increase our product categories as well as undergo a series of business developments particularly in the areas of technology and marketing. NewMedia SPARK is a great investor for us with its unprecedented knowledge of the online business world with a portfolio to match. We are delighted that Tom is joining our board: his long-standing experience and reputation, as well as passion and commitment to our business, is amazing."     Tom Teichman added: "Notonthehighstreet.com is a great addition to SPARK's existing portfolio and I am looking forward to bringing our expertise in digital start-ups to the business. Holly and Sophie have that contagious passion we know as 'the spark' - an undefined magic ingredient that we share for notonthehighstreet.com. Together we are going to fully exploit and grow notonthehighstreet.com's potential to create something of real value in the small business and digital worlds."     Note to Editors: Holly Tucker, Sophie Cornish and Tom Teichman are available for interview.       Notonthehighstreet.com     Notonthehighstreet.com was an overnight success when it launched on 3 April 2006. An extensive PR campaign drove 16,000 unique users to the site on the first day and now thousands of unique users visit the site daily and over 200 national and regional newspaper and magazines have featured news and features about the site. In October 2006, notonthehighstreet.com was named a top 50 e-boutique by The Independent.     Notonthehighstreet.com now brings over five hundred independent small UK businesses together to sell over 10,000 products under one URL. Notonthehighstreet.com has carefully chosen each small business for its innovative, well-made products to inspire shoppers looking for style, originality and quality, but who never seem to be able to find it on the high street. Now they can browse and buy a wide range of products from this unique small business marketplace using a single on-line shopping basket.     From lampshades to linen, bracelets to handbags, cushions to kids clothes, scarves to stationery, notonthehighstreet.com has a great range of beautifully made, original products and services. Thousands of products are available to buy from a choice of 12 categories: home and garden, art and ceramics, baby & child, jewellery, fashion, health & beauty, stationery & office, food and drink, party & play, pets, travel & getaway and treats & flowers.       Among the unique editorial features of notonthehighstreet.com:       --  Each partner (small business or designer) has its own URL and          'homepage' so that shoppers can read background information          about them and their latest news and events. Partners are in          control of the products they put on the site and sell directly          to the shopper. In effect they have their own mini website          under the notonthehighstreet.com umbrella.       --  Notonthehighstreet.com has a unique gift finder service with          the ability to search by price, occasion, for a specific type          of person, even making recommendations depending on their          style and personality. Shoppers can also create their own wish          lists for their friends and family to take a look at on the          site.       --  A very extensive features and product finder facility at          notonthehighstreet.com with several categories ranging from          those who know exactly what they are looking for to others who          want to discover products by new talented small businesses.       --  Editorial themed features are constantly updated: from 10          gifts under GBP 10 to the latest eco and organic shopping buys          as well as seasonal and special occasion present updates.       www.notonthehighstreet.com        CONTACT: Notonthehighstreet.com               Julie Turner, +33 (0)6 25 28 72 82               press@notonthehighstreet.com        SOURCE: Notonthehighstreet.com  Copyright Business Wire 2007     Order free Annual Report for NewMedia SPARK PLC  Visit http://djnweurope.ar.wilink.com/?ticker=GB0008550286 or call +44 (0)208 391 6028  (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 03:00 ET (08:00 GMT)

Headline: : HudBay Second Half 2006 Exploration Update
Story: WINNIPEG, MANITOBA -- (MARKET WIRE) -- 03/02/07 --    HudBay Minerals Inc. (TSX: HBM) (HudBay) announces results from its second half 2006 exploration in northern Manitoba and Saskatchewan. Illustrations and previously released data are available at www.hudbayminerals.com.     During the second half of 2006, approximately 23,738 meters of diamond drilling in 39 surface drill holes was completed, with a focus on mineral deposit targets and structural targets. HudBay's subsidiary, Hudson Bay Exploration and Development Company Limited (HBED) managed the exploration in the Flin Flon Greenstone Belt and the majority of the exploration was funded by flow-through financing.     "Drill results continued to be encouraging at the Bur deposit and at the Talbot Lake deposit where one intersection was 12.44% copper over 9.65 meters," said Peter Jones, President & CEO. "For 2007 we have increased our total exploration program expenditure plans to $37 million, making it one of the largest in Canada."     Exploration results reported in this release exclude results from exploration within HudBay operating mines and exploration at locations other than northern Manitoba and Saskatchewan. HudBay recently announced that its January 1, 2007 aggregate estimated mineral reserves and mineral resources increased compared to those at January 1, 2006, after taking into account 2006 ore production.        Mineral Deposit Targets        Bur Deposit     The Bur deposit is 22 kilometres from the Snow Lake concentrator. Drilling at the Bur deposit in the second half of 2006 improved the definition of mineralization. As a result of earlier drilling, HudBay announced in December 2006 plans to invest approximately $8.5 million at the Bur deposit for additional in-fill diamond drilling, underground excavations to extract a 10,000 tonne ore sample, obtaining production permits as well as completion of a feasibility study. During the second half of 2006, 1,150 meters of drilling were completed. Notable intersections included:      - 3.25% Cu, 17.65% Zn over 1.21 meters in drill hole BZS015;  - 5.34% Cu, 4.99% Zn over 1.47 meters in drill hole BZS022;       Drilling will continue in 2007 as part of the $8.5 million planned investment.        Talbot Lake Deposit        The Talbot Lake deposit is located 83 km from the Snow Lake concentrator.     In the second half of 2006, 7,084 meters were drilled in eleven holes. Ten of those holes intersected mineralization.     The last drill hole of the program - hole TLS020, made a very encouraging intersection which assayed 11.16 grams/tonne gold, 184.37 grams/tonne silver, 12.44% copper and 3.50% zinc over 9.65 meters.      Other main zone intersections were:    - 1.09% Cu, 6.32% Zn over 1.69 meters in drill hole TLS010;  - 4.24% Cu, 0.59% Zn over 3.15 meters in drill hole TLS011;  - 0.62% Cu, 1.03% Zn over 1.72 meters in drill hole TLS012:  - 2.15% Cu, 1.68% Zn over 1.29 meters in drill hole TLS013;  - 0.10% Cu, 8.13% Zn over 0.74 meters in drill hole TLS014;  - 0.94% Cu, 0.53% Zn over 1.66 meters in drill hole TLS015;  - 0.61% Cu, 0.08% Zn over 1.20 meters in drill hole TLS016;  - 0.47% Cu, 0.40% Zn over 9.70 meters in drill hole TLS017;  - 0.60% Cu, 2.63% Zn over 2.09 meters in drill hole TLS018;  - TLS019 was abandoned       HudBay will follow up exploration of the significant mineralization intersected in drill hole TLS020 at the earliest opportunity.        Structural Targets        Chisel Target     Drilling continued at the previously mined Chisel and Photo Lake properties, and on targets related to the operating Chisel North mine. 5388 meters were drilled in 10 parent drill holes and two wedge cuts.        Notable intersections included:      - 0.10% Cu, 3.34% Zn over 1.00 meter in drill hole CH0602;  - 0.13% Cu, 7.65% Zn over 0.69 meters in drill hole CH0602W1       Drill holes CH0603, CH0505, CH0606, CH0607, CH0608 and DUB166 tested Quantec Titan 24 deep penetrating geophysical anomalies identified in a survey completed in the first quarter of 2006. Although no notable assay intervals were intersected, CH0606 intersected 7.71 meters of massive pyrite from 531.71 to 539.42 meters coincident with a Titan 24 anomaly and also with the Chisel Mine horizon. Additional exploration is planned to test this mineralization in 2007.     Two drill holes, DUB165 and DUB167 tested targets below the now closed Photo Lake mine. There were no notable intersections in DUB165 however DUB167 intersected a wide interval of quartz-staurolite-biotite-chlorite gneiss with disseminated chalcopyrite (copper) stringer mineralization.        Flin Flon, Manitoba     2,130 meters were drilled in four holes testing the hanging wall stratigraphy and along the strike of the Flin Flon - 777 mine. There were no notable intersections.        Flin Flon, Saskatchewan     4,774 meters were drilled in five holes that tested a structurally repeated fault block of the Flin Flon mine stratigraphy located deep in the footwall of the Flin Flon mine, previously intersected by holes completed in 2005. There were no notable mineral intersections.        Geophysical Targets     738 meters were drilled in three holes east and south of Snow Lake to test geophysical anomalies. There were no notable intersections.      2007 Expenditure Plans(i)  =------------------------    =---------------------------------------------------------------------  Flin Flon Greenstone Belt                                        ($ millions)  Electromagnetic anomalies                   8.5  Known deposits                              4.5  Operating mines                             4.0  Geophysics                                  3.0  Structural targets                          3.0  Administration/miscellaneous                3.0                                                       26.0    Other Locations    Balmat District                             4.0  Unallocated                                 7.0                                                       11.0                                                    -------  Total planned 2007 expenditure                      $37.0 million    =---------------------------------------------------------------------    (i)All expenditures are preliminary estimates and actual expenditures may     vary depending on several factors       HudBay's exploration properties include approximately 380,000 hectares in the prolific Flin Flon Greenstone Belt of Manitoba and Saskatchewan and approximately 20,000 hectares in the Balmat district of New York state. In addition, HudBay owns the Tom zinc/lead mineral deposit in the Yukon and holds an option to purchase the adjacent Jason zinc/lead mineral property. Additional exploration assets include copper exploration properties in Chile and zinc exploration properties in Southwestern Ontario.        2006 HudBay Procedures     Exploration core drilling was either NQ or BQ size. The core was logged and mineralized intersections were marked for sampling and assaying, by HBED employed geologists. The marked intersections or intervals were sawn in half by a diamond saw and one half of the core was placed in plastic bags and tagged with unique sample numbers, while the second half was returned to the core box and stored.     Each bagged core sample was transported to the Hudson Bay Mining and Smelting Co., Limited's assay laboratory in Flin Flon, Manitoba where it was dried, crushed and pulverized and a 250-gram sample was prepared for assaying. From each 250 gram sample 0.25 grams was removed and leached in aqua regia and analyzed by ICP-AES for Ag, Cu, Zn, As, Pb, Ni and Fe. Also from the 250-gram sample, 15 grams was removed for gold determination by fire assaying with Atomic Absorption finish.     Assaying integrity is monitored internally with a quality control program, which includes the use of assay sample standards, blanks, duplicates and repeats and externally through national and international programs. In addition, within each group of 20 core samples, one core sample has a second 250 gram split collected for check assaying at Acme Analytical Laboratories Ltd. in Vancouver, B.C.        News Release and Attachments     The news release and attached tables provide core lengths and additionally where indicated, horizontal or vertical lengths of mineralization intersected. True widths are not provided. Where metal assays are provided for intersections they are either a single assay of a sample of the entire intersection length or a composite of assays calculated from interval weighted assays over the intersection length.     The data herein and the contents of this news release have been reviewed by Kelly Gilmore, B.Sc. P. Geo., Chief Exploration Geologist with HBED, who is a Qualified Person, within the meaning of National Instrument 43-101, with the ability and authority to verify the authenticity and validity of the data.     Attached to this news release are tables showing the second half 2006 drill results. Graphics together with prior periods and additional drill results may be found at the HudBay web site, www.hudbayminerals.com.        About HudBay Minerals Inc.     HudBay Minerals Inc. is an integrated mining company that operates mines, concentrators and a metal production complex in northern Manitoba and Saskatchewan. The company also owns a zinc oxide production facility in Ontario, the White Pine Copper Refinery in Michigan and the Balmat zinc mine in New York state.        HudBay is a member of the S&P/TSX Composite Index.        Forward-Looking Information     (MORE TO FOLLOW) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 16:25 ET (21:25 GMT)

Headline: US Airways Computer Problem Delays Hundreds In Charlotte, NC
Story: CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP)--A problem with a computerized reservations system caused delays for about 500 US Airways passengers Sunday at the airline's largest hub, airline officials said.   Lines were backed up for about an hour and a half when US Airways' automated kiosks didn't work at Charlotte-Douglas International Airport, said Phil Gee, spokesman for the Tempe, Ariz.-based airline.   Delays also occurred at Philadelphia International Airport.   The lines, which still existed through Sunday morning, happened because passengers were forced to wait for ticket counter agents to issue their boarding passes.   "We are aware of some folks missing their flights because the lines are long. No flights are being delayed or canceled," Gee said. "We're waiving the re-booking fee."   Early Sunday, the airline was trying to merge the reservation systems of US Airways and America West when the computer problem happened. The two airlines merged in 2005.     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 11:04 ET (16:04 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: : 012 Golden Lines Reports Record Results for 2006
Story: - Revenues Up 12% to NIS 715M with 23% Rise in Operating Income, 85% Increase in Profit Before Taxes -       PETACH TIKVA, Israel, March 4 /PRNewswire-FirstCall/ -- 012 Golden Lines Ltd., a wholly-owned subsidiary (through Smile Communications) of Internet Gold  (Nasdaq: IGLD) that will soon complete its statutory merger with Internet Gold's wholly-owned subsidiary Smile.Communications Ltd., today reported its unaudited financial results for the year ended December 31, 2006.          Highlights      * Record revenues, up 12% year-over-year (YOY) to NIS 715 million      * 20% YOY growth in broadband customer base      * Poised for a steep ramp-up of domestic telephony services: in February        2007, 012 Golden Lines became the first Israeli company to be granted a        permanent license to provide domestic VOB (Voice Over Broadband)        telephony services in Israel. This positions it to begin an accelerated        ramp up from its existing 15,000 VOB customer base with the goal of        securing a significant share of Israel's over NIS 5 billion domestic        telephony market.      * Merger with Smile.Communications: 012 Golden Lines recently began the        process of merging with Smile.Communications. The merger is expected to        create a company with 2007 revenues of more than NIS 1.2 billion and        improved profitability and cash flow as a result of synergies between        the two companies.        Financial Results     Revenues for 2006 reached a record NIS 715 million, an increase of 12% compared to NIS 639 million in 2005. Operating profit for the year reached NIS 83 million, an increase of 23% compared to NIS 68 million in 2005. On a non-GAAP basis, EBITDA* (defined as income before financial income (expenses), net; other income (expenses), net; income taxes; depreciation and amortization) for 2006 increased by 13% to NIS 147 million compared to NIS 130 million recorded in the previous year.     Net income for the year was NIS 41 million. This includes the effect of a one-time charge of NIS 6 million relating to 012 Golden Lines' uncompleted initial public offering. Excluding this one-time charge, the Company's net income in 2006 reached NIS 47 million, an increase of 74% compared with NIS 27 million in 2005.        Non-GAAP Measure     EBITDA is a non-GAAP financial measure which is not in accordance with GAAP. The company believes that this non-GAAP financial measure provides meaningful supplemental information to both management and investors that is indicative of the Company's results and facilitates comparison of results across reporting periods. The Company used this non-GAAP measure when evaluating its financial results as well as for internal resource management, planning and forecasting purposes. This non-GAAP measure should not be viewed in isolation from or as a substitute for the Company's financial results in accordance with GAAP. For more information, please see the table included at the end of this release.        Comments of Management     Commenting on the results, Ms. Stella Handler, CEO of 012 Golden Lines, said, "We are proud to report an excellent year across all parameters. We reported record revenues along with strong operating profit, net profit and EBITDA, the tangible results of the professional execution delivered throughout the year by each of our business segments.     "As we move into 2007, our goal is to continue building each of our businesses while simultaneously merging with Smile.Communications, building a forceful new company with a significant share of several large markets and annual revenues above of NIS 1.2 billion. We will work to further expand our Internet access customer base, adding significant numbers of new residential and business customers. In parallel, we intend to immediately begin taking advantage of our new VOB license with the roll-out of an attractive variety of innovative services, to make VOB one of our strongest growth drivers during the next several years."     012 Golden Lines is Israel's largest provider of domestic telephony over broadband (VOB) services, and the first company to receive a permanent VOB license. Over the past two years, it has been offering VOB services under a limited temporary license and it now has approximately 15,000 residential and business customers.        Expected post-merger positioning     After the completion of the 012 Golden Lines statutory merger with Smile.Communications, the merged company will be positioned as one of Israel's strongest communications groups with a one third market share of both Internet Access (ISP) and International Telephony (ILD) markets.        About 012 Golden Lines     012 Golden Lines is one of Israel's leading communications companies with approximately 16% of Israel's Broadband Internet Access market and more than 30% of its International Telephony market. 012 Golden Lines was Israel's first company to offer domestic Telephony Over Broadband (VOB) services and is the first to have received a permanent VOB license.     Established in 1996, 012 Golden Lines has grown from its beginning as an International Telephony operator to become a full-service Communications Services Provider, offering Broadband Internet Access, Domestic and International Telephony, Data Services and a broad range of Value Added Services, including Data Security, VPN, Data Storage, IP Roaming and Network Management.        About Internet Gold     Internet Gold is Israel's leading IP Group with a major presence across all Internet-related sectors. Its Smile.Communications segment offers a variety of Internet access and related value-added services, international telephony and enterprise/IT integration services. Its Smile.Media segment manages a growing portfolio of Internet portals and e-Commerce sites.     Internet Gold is part of the Eurocom Communications Group. Its shares trade on the Nasdaq Global Market and on the Tel Aviv Stock Exchange.     For additional information about Internet Gold, please visit its investors' site at http://www.igld.com.          For further information, please contact:      Ms. Idit Azulay, Internet Gold      +972 3 939-9848      idita@co.zahav.net.il                      *   RECONCILIATION TABLE OF NON-GAAP MEASURES                           (NIS in millions)(Unaudited)                                                    2006        2005                                               ------      ------      Net Income as reported                     41          27      Taxes on income                            21           6      Other expenses                              6           -      Financial expense                          15          35      Depreciation & Amortization                64          62                                               ------------------      EBITDA as adjusted                        147         130                                               ==================      SOURCE  012 Golden Lines Ltd.       /CONTACT: Ms. Idit Azulay, Internet Gold, +972-9-939-9848, idita@co.zahav.net.il      /Web site: http://www.igld.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 08:05 ET (13:05 GMT)

Headline: Singapore Says 12 Bidders For Island-wide Broadband Network
Story: SINGAPORE (Dow Jones)--Singapore's telecommunications regulator said a total of 12 companies and consortiums are in the running to build a broadband network on the island.   These "pre-qualified" bidders will provide feedback on government proposals for the nationwide network before a tender is opened in mid-August, the Infocomm Development Authority said in a statement Saturday.   The government wants the network to be capable of speeds of 1 gigabits a second or more and to connect to 95% of businesses and homes by 2012. A wireless component will extend broadband Internet access to public places.   The companies bidding alone are Japan's Nippon Telegraph & Telephone Corp. (9432.TO), Siemens AG (SIE.XE) and two Singapore-based telephone companies, Singapore Telecommunications Ltd. (Z74.SG) and StarHub Ltd. (Z81.SG).   A third Singapore telecommunications company, MobileOne Ltd. (M31.SG), is a member of a consortium led by Hong Kong Broadband Network Ltd.   SingTel is also leading a consortium comprising Australian investment bank Babcock & Brown Ltd. (BNB.AU), Australia's Macquarie Bank Ltd. (MBL.AU) and Cisco Systems Inc. (CSCO), while Babcock is also a member of a consortium led by the Singapore unit of French telecommunications maker Alcatel-Lucent (ALU.FR).   Wall Street investment bank Citigroup Inc. (C) is a member of two consortia.   The IDA said the successful bid will be announced by the end of December.     -By Singapore Bureau; Dow Jones Newswires; 65-6415-4150; djnews.singapore.bureau@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 04:15 ET (09:15 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Wal-Mart Plots To Scupper Tesco's US Launch - Report
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--U.S. supermarket giant Wal-Mart Stores Inc. (WMT) has charged a former Tesco (TSCO.LN) executive to come up with plans to thwart the U.K. retailer's debut in the U.S., The Sunday Times reports.   Wal-Mart's response is being coordinated by David Wild, a former international managing director of Tesco, the paper said. Among options being considered is the launch of rival stores or adapting existing Wal-Marts to take on Tesco's planned green mini-supermarkets, it added.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.timesonline.com   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9295     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 08:14 ET (13:14 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Australia's Seven Network, PBL Eyeing CanWest NZ Ops -Report
Story: WELLINGTON (Dow Jones)--Australia's Seven Network Ltd. (SEV.AU) and Publishing and Broadcasting Ltd. (PBL.AU)  could be frontrunners to buy CanWest Global Communications Corp. (CWG) New Zealand operations, the Dominion Post reported Monday.    Details are sketchy but market sources suggest there has been some buying interest, the report said. It said Seven Network and PBL are working with private equity partners for their respective bids.   CanWest Global, 70% owner of CanWest MediaWorks (MWL.NZ), is exploring opportunities for its Australasian assets ahead of this year's liberalization of Australian media ownership laws.     Newspaper web site: http://www.stuff.co.nz     -Wellington Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; 64-4-471-5990; djnews.wellington@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 16:01 ET (21:01 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

On a rolling 12-month basis to January 31, 2007, revenues from continuing  operations increased over 23.7 percent to $375.3 million compared to  $303.4 million for the prior year period. Earnings from continuing operations,  on the same rolling 12-month basis, increased by 56.4 percent to $38.0 million  from $24.3 million for the corresponding period last year.        Year to date ended January 31, 2007        Revenues for the nine-month period ending January 31, 2007 increased  25.9 percent to $286.4 million from $227.5 million for the corresponding  period last year. More than half of this increase in revenues is related to  Latin America.      Gross margins for the nine-month period were 31.3 percent compared to 28.3  percent last year due mainly to an improving pricing environment. With the  increase in revenues and improving gross margins, gross profit for the  nine-month period increased by 38.9 percent to $89.6 million compared to  $64.5 million for the prior year period.      General and administrative expenses increased to $23.6 million compared to  $20.9 million for the same period last year. The increase is primarily due to  additions to management to accommodate growth and salary increases across the  operations.      Other expenses were $7.1 million for the nine-month period compared to  $5.3 million for the same period last year due, in part, to an increase in  incentive provisions as a result of improved profitability and increased  provision for bad debt, muted by a gain on sale of investments.      Foreign exchange loss was $0.4 million for the nine-month period compared  to $0.8 million in the prior year period.      Short-term interest revenue was $0.3 million for the nine-month period  compared to an expense of $0.6 million last year, while interest on long-term  debt was $1.9 million compared to $2.1 million for the same period last year.      Amortization expense increased to $14.6 million for the nine-month period,  compared to $12.9 million for the same period last year, as a result of  increased investment in equipment.      The provision for income tax for the nine-month period was $13.6 million  compared to $5.9 million for the prior year period reflecting the increase in  pre-tax earnings.      Earnings from continuing operations for the nine-month period were  $28.7 million or $1.24 per share ($1.22 per share diluted) compared to  $15.9 million or $0.70 per share ($0.69 per share diluted) for the same period  last year.      Gain from discontinued operations was $12.2 million or $0.53 per share  compared to a gain of $1.0 million or $0.05 per share for the same period last  year. Discontinued operations include the sale of the manufacturing division  and the termination of operations in China.      Resulting net earnings were $41.0 million or $1.77 per share ($1.74 per  share diluted) compared to $17.0 million or $0.75 per share ($0.73 per share  diluted) for the same period last year. Based in Moncton, New Brunswick, Major Drilling Group International Inc.  is one of the world's largest metals and minerals contract drilling service  companies. Headline: TNK-BP's Orenburgneft Oil Pipe Shut Following Leak -Report
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Russia's environmental agency Saturday said environment violations at Orenburgneft, a subsidiary of Anglo-Russian firm TNK-BP Holdings (TNBP.RS), had led to an oil pipeline leak that threatened water supplies, news agency Reuters said, citing Russia's Interfax news agency.   "The problem is a pipeline accident at Orenburgneft's Krasnoyarskoye oil field, which led to oil leaking into the Bolshoi Kinel River," Oleg Mitvol, deputy head of the agency was quoted by Interfax as saying, Reuters said.   Mitvol said the oil flows through the pipeline have stopped and the environmental agency was trying to assess the environmental damage. The oil leak occurred on Feb. 28, Reuters said.   Local media reported last week that about five tons of oil products had leaked into the river in the Orenburg region.   TNK-BP couldn't be reached for comment on Sunday.   Mitvol said the worn-out machinery at Orenburgneft, which produced 120 million barrels of crude oil in 2006, had caused the leak. The leak posed a danger to water supplies in the eastern Russian region, which borders Kazakhstan, Reuters reported.     Company Web site: http://www.tnk-bp.com     -By Alex MacDonald, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9328; alex.macdonald@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 06:07 ET (11:07 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: UPDATE: TNK-BP Orenburgneft Oil Pipe Shut After Leak -Agency
Story: (This updates an item published at 1351 GMT with additional background information and quotes.)     LONDON (Dow Jones)--Russia's environmental agency confirmed Sunday that environment violations at Orenburgneft, a subsidiary of Anglo-Russian firm TNK-BP Holdings (TNBP.RS), had led to an oil pipeline leak that threatened water supplies.   "There was a problem with the Orenburgneft's oil pipeline going across the Bolshoi Kinel river in the Orenburg region," Oleg Mitvol, deputy head of Russia' environmental watchdog Rosprirodnadzor, told Dow Jones Newswires. The pipeline pumps oil products from the Orenburgneft's Krasnoyarskoye oil field.   Mitvol said that initial tests show that a minimum of 150 tons or 1,100 barrels of oil products spilt into the river. The pipeline was shut down on Feb. 28, but Mitvol said it wasn't clear how long the pipe had been leaking oil products into the river.   "We don't know how many days or weeks oil has been going into the river," Mitvol said.    He added the environment agency was working to purify the water supplies of cities affected by the oil spill. The Kinel river flows into the much larger Volga river via the Samara river, posing a danger to water supplies in the eastern Russian region, which borders Kazakhstan.   Mitvol said the agency will provide more details about the size and impact of the oil spill on Monday. The leak had already contaminated water supplies at three small cities 60 kilometers from the source of the spill, Mitvol said. The oil spill was caused by a rupture in a worn out section of the pipe that crosses underneath the river.   One of TNK-BP's parent companies, BP PLC (BP), is already under intense scrutiny after a corroded transit pipe at its giant Prudoe Bay oil field in Alaska ruptured in March, resulting in an oil leak.    Mitvol said that TNK-BP had failed to reinforce the aging pipeline in accordance with environmental standards regarding river crossings. Pipelines that cross rivers must have two pipes: one inside the other. The leaking oil pipe only had one layer, Mitvol said.   The TNK-BP joint venture is already facing uncertainty after Russian state authorities began threatening to revoke TNK-BP's license to develop the Kovykta gas field in eastern Siberia due to underproduction rather than environmental problems at the field.   Mitvol has become famous in Russia for his aggressive stance against oil companies, especially foreign ones, both over their environmental policies and other issues not directly in his portfolio.   Spokespeople for TNK-BP couldn't be reached for comment on Sunday.   TNK-BP is half-owned by BP and half-owned by a consortium of Russian investors.     Company Web site: http://www.tnk-bp.com     -By Alex MacDonald, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9328; alex.macdonald@dowjones.com     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 11:49 ET (16:49 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.

Headline: Goldman Sachs To Set Up Internal Joint Venture - Report
Story: LONDON (Dow Jones)--Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (GS) is establishing a $1 billion internal joint venture that may help forge closer ties between competing arms of the U.S. investment bank, The Sunday Telegraph newspaper reports.   The launch of Goldman Sachs Direct Partners will link Goldman's powerful Principal Investment arm - a unit that invests in external deals - and the bank's investment banking division, the paper said.   Goldman officials couldn't immediately be reached for comment.   Newspaper Web site: http://www.telegraph.co.uk   -London Bureau, Dow Jones Newswires; +44 (0)20 7842 9295     (END) Dow Jones Newswires  March 04, 2007 06:28 ET (11:28 GMT)  Copyright (c) 2007 Dow Jones & Company, Inc.
